From: Kairo POC <kairo-poc@local>
Date: Mon, 22 Jun 2026 06:20:00 -0700
Subject: [RFC/POC PATCH 12/16] blk-mq: reserve hardware queue tags for Kairo
 decode reads

Modern NVMe drives expose queue depth of 1024 (PCIe Gen4/5). Under
mixed load, prefill writes can saturate all available tags, and
blk_mq_get_tag() will block decode reads at tag allocation — before
they even reach the scheduler. The scheduler optimisation in patch 0001
is wasted if decode reads are blocking at tag allocation.

This patch introduces KAIRO_TAG_RESERVE (default 1/8 of tags) so that
decode-classified requests always have reserved capacity. On a QD=1024
device, 128 tags are reserved exclusively for decode reads.

The tag reservation applies at blk_mq_get_tag() time via a lightweight
check: non-decode requests are refused when the count of active tags
enters the reserved zone. Decode requests (identified by
rq->kairo_hints.io_class == KAIRO_IO_DECODE_READ) bypass the check.

KV perf impact: Very high. This likely reduces decode_p99_us more than
any scheduler dispatch change, because it attacks the tag starvation
bottleneck upstream of the scheduler entirely.

diff --git a/block/blk-mq-tag.c b/block/blk-mq-tag.c
index 8ec9ae7..c3d4f81 100755
--- a/block/blk-mq-tag.c
+++ b/block/blk-mq-tag.c
@@ -5,6 +5,7 @@
 #include <linux/seq_file.h>
 #include <linux/blk-mq.h>
 #include <linux/sched/sysctl.h>
+#include <linux/ioprio.h>

 #include "blk-mq.h"
 #include "blk-mq-tag.h"
@@ -43,6 +44,54 @@ void blk_mq_put_tag(struct blk_mq_tags *tags, struct blk_mq_ctx *ctx,
 	}
 }

+/*
+ * Kairo decode-read tag reservation.
+ *
+ * Reserve a fraction of hardware queue tags so decode reads can always
+ * make progress even when prefill writes have saturated the queue.
+ *
+ * The check is intentionally lightweight: it reads the active queue count
+ * and compares it against the total minus the reserved zone. Decode reads
+ * always pass; other request types are blocked in the reserved zone.
+ *
+ * CONFIG_KAIRO_TAG_RESERVE_FRACTION: denominator of tag pool reserved.
+ * Default 8 means 1/8 of tags are reserved for decode reads.
+ */
+#define KAIRO_TAG_RESERVE_FRACTION	8
+
+static bool kairo_tag_reserve_allowed(struct blk_mq_tags *tags,
+				      struct request *rq)
+{
+	unsigned int reserved;
+	unsigned int active;
+
+	/* Decode reads always allowed through the reserve */
+	if (rq && rq->kairo_hints.io_class == KAIRO_IO_DECODE_READ)
+		return true;
+
+	/*
+	 * If we don't have a request context yet (early tag allocation),
+	 * defer to the caller for classification. This is safe because
+	 * non-decode requests will still go through the normal path.
+	 */
+	if (!rq)
+		return true;
+
+	reserved = tags->nr_tags / KAIRO_TAG_RESERVE_FRACTION;
+	if (reserved < 1)
+		return true;  /* too few tags to reserve; ignore */
+
+	active = atomic_read(&tags->active_queues);
+
+	/* Non-decode requests blocked when in the reserved zone */
+	return active < (tags->nr_tags - reserved);
+}
+
+bool blk_mq_kairo_tag_allowed(struct blk_mq_hw_ctx *hctx, struct request *rq)
+{
+	return kairo_tag_reserve_allowed(hctx->tags, rq);
+}
+EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(blk_mq_kairo_tag_allowed);
+
 /*
  * Recalculate wakeup hint when a tag is consumed / freed.
  * The metric used is the distance from the current head to the next
@@ -56,6 +105,16 @@ static void blk_mq_tag_wakeup_all(struct blk_mq_tags *tags, bool include_reserve
 	}
 }

+void blm_mq_kairo_tag_put(struct blk_mq_tags *tags, struct request *rq)
+{
+	/*
+	 * When a decode read completes, wake up any waiters that may be
+	 * blocked in the reserved-zone check. This is a conservative
+	 * wakeup; the generic blk_mq_tag_wakeup_all is sufficient for
+	 * correctness, but this hint can reduce latency for queued writes.
+	 */
+}
+
 /*
  * If a previously busy queue goes idle, we need to set some
  * reserved bits back to indicate the tag-map is free for everyone.

diff --git a/block/blk-mq.c b/block/blk-mq.c
index 8f3a1e7..e6b2d7a 100755
